&lt;p&gt;Screenshot &lt;a href="http://www7.pic-upload.de/17.12.12/r2be1k4nlggz.png"&gt;http://www7.pic-upload.de/17.12.12/r2...&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
 </title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/915/how-to-edit-theme-of-kde-based-windows/?answer=6645#post-id-6645</link><description> 2015-08-20, ArchLinux, whole plasma-meta is installed.

The solution posted here didn't work. After checking Arch Wiki, apparently Qt apps check `DESKTOP_SESSION` environment variable to setup their themes accordingly. In my case it was pointing to path of i3. I did `export DESKTOP_SESSION=kde` and now Qt apps work perfectly, no more ugly theme with missing icons.

edit: `XDG_CURRENT_DESKTOP=kde` works too.</description><pubDate>Sun, 20 Sep 2015 15:55:32 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/915/how-to-edit-theme-of-kde-based-windows/?answer=6645#post-id-6645</guid></item><item><title>Comment by i3convert for &lt;p&gt;2015-08-20, ArchLinux, whole plasma-meta is installed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The solution posted here didn't work. After checking Arch Wiki, apparently Qt apps check &lt;code&gt;DESKTOP_SESSION&lt;/code&gt; environment variable to setup their themes accordingly. In my case it was pointing to path of i3. I did &lt;code&gt;export DESKTOP_SESSION=kde&lt;/code&gt; and now Qt apps work perfectly, no more ugly theme with missing icons.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;edit: &lt;code&gt;XDG_CURRENT_DESKTOP=kde&lt;/code&gt; works too.&lt;/p&gt;
</title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/915/how-to-edit-theme-of-kde-based-windows/?comment=6647#comment-6647</link><description>This works on a pretty plain Fedora installation too! Thanks!</description><pubDate>Sun, 20 Sep 2015 16:46:38 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/915/how-to-edit-theme-of-kde-based-windows/?comment=6647#comment-6647</guid></item><item><title>Answer by Oliver for &lt;p&gt;Hey,&lt;/p&gt;

